On February 24, 2009, President Obama met with Japanese Prime Minister Aso to discuss various topics, including the global economic crisis and bilateral cooperation. They emphasized the importance of the U.S.-Japan Alliance and the need to modernize it through joint realignment initiatives. They also agreed to work together to stimulate demand, help other countries respond to the crisis, unfreeze credit markets, and resist protectionism. In terms of regional issues, they pledged to work through the Six-Party process to eliminate North Korea's nuclear program and address other concerns, such as Japan's abducted citizens. They also discussed stabilizing Afghanistan and appreciated Japan's contributions in the region. Climate change was seen as a priority for both nations, and they discussed ways to collaborate, including assisting developing nations and conducting joint research on clean energy technology.